\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7756011 Glen:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid4470500\charrsid7756011 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9184388\charrsid7756011 March of the Dimes it
\rquote s called, and it was, I don\rquote t know when it began, or when it got that name, 
but people would contribute dimes to the support of polio research, and children would be the people out there trying to mobilise support for the Organisation, and I can remember being at supermarkets, and I suppose we were Cub Scouts, young children like
 
that.  But it was a real scourge in childhood at that time.  And then when we had children, and they discovered a pill that would solve this problem, and all of our children got immunised against polio.  I remember what a tremendous transition that was, f
rom something that could kill you, to something that would save children from going through it.  That was \lquote 62/\rquote 
63, because we had just come to Berkeley, and they were campaigning throughout the city, to make sure that all kids were immunised, getting their shots.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7756011 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid9184388\charrsid7756011 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9184388\charrsid7756011 
And I think you used the phrase, you felt that you were \'93blessed\'94?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7756011 Glen:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid4470500\charrsid7756011 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9184388\charrsid7756011 
Yes.  I thought of it as a miracle, because so many - all I could see around me - were casualties.  And I can remember somebody had given me a radio to listen to, in th
e ward, and sometimes I would fall asleep at night with the radio on, and the night nurse would get very very upset.  And every time that would happen, she would wheel me out into the hallway and leave me out there.  And, you know, something like that cou
ld spook a little child, but it really never did.  I just thought of her as a very mean old nurse, you know!  (LAUGHS) \'85 I know that hospitalisation can be a very adverse experience and have negative consequences for kids \endash 
