\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid7756011 Glen:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid4470500\charrsid7756011 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9184388\charrsid7756011 
Well, I think there was probably my mother\rquote s primary contribution that one should live a life of gratitude, being grateful for what you have, rather than resentful for what you don\rquote 
t have.  This was very much a Christian perspective on the world, and I thi
nk it was a [valuable] perspective, because it enabled me to deal with her passing.  [I could] realise that I have nothing to complain about here, that I have a lot to be grateful for.  That is a whole philosophy of ageing.  Instead of being so upset abou
t what you can\rquote t do any more, [one should be] grateful for what you\rquote ve been able to do, and what you still can do.  It\rquote 
s a totally different - your glass is half full rather than half empty!  (LAUGHS)  So I think it was my mother and the kind of philosophy she had.
