r lives.  As adolescents, they seemed quite lost, and they didn\rquote t do well at school, and, and when Jean looks at them at age 40, she can\rquote t believe how well they\rquote ve done. What she doesn\rquote t do is ask, \'93Well, what kind of}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11341284\charrsid7756011  life have these people led?"  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9184388\charrsid7756011 Some of these people went into the War, and some didn\rquote 
t.  And it made a lot of difference.  The kids, the boys, who left home and went into the military, often did so as soon as they could, to get away from home, and you can see the developmental change in their l
ife, up to age 40.  They gained self-confidence, they gained a sense of assertiveness, and they were doing quite well in their jobs, they\rquote 
d completed their educations, and yet Jean never really looked at this at all.  She really was looking at a different thing.  I always use this as an example [of the Instit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11341284\charrsid7756011 
ute's contextual perspective]. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9184388\charrsid7756011 Lives are lived in a changing world, and if you study those lives longitudinally, over time, and ignore the context, the situations they\rquote 
re living through, you\rquote re going to miss most of the story.  And I think that\rquote s the big point, for all of these longitudinal studies that are going on throughout the world.  We really do live in an age of longitudinal studies, and it\rquote 
s so easy for people to ignore context, and just do the study and forget about where they\rquote ve been.  But you can\rquote 
t do that without missing [a large part] of the story, and I think that probably is the number one point that life course theory and research has to offer, that lives are always lived in context \endash  historical and spatial \endash  and you can\rquote 
t look at historical time without looking at where it\rquote s happening.  And you can\rquote t look at where it\rquote s happening without asking when it\rquote s happening.  And then those changes make a difference in how we live our life, and that 
process has everything to do with who we become and how we are, psycho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid11341284\charrsid7756011 logically, at life at age 50.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid9184388\charrsid7756011 So I think this is the major contribution that we can make to the study of lives and human development: is to get the people who are doing the studies, to realise that it\rquote 
s not just simply a cohort sequential design that they need.  They need to pay attention to the changes that are taking place in the lives of these people, in a macro sense as well as a micro sense, and [to bring them] together.
